segments.text: I came out of this program in 71.
I think many of us did that were more generalist.
I think there's some positives and negatives on that.
I think many times you're so general that people don't think you can really do functional planning.
My whole life has been saying if you know how to plan, you can plan for anything, no matter what.
And you can do comprehensive planning.
You can deal with strategic planning issues.
You can deal with functional issues.
And you can become an expert in health planning.
I don't know where the future is in this whole business.
I'm just around so many people that planning is so foreign that you have to sell your wares for other things.
You have to sell on, you know, like I'm in policy development.
Every action that I get the governor to act upon
It's a little planning document.
I gather facts.

I do the analytical work necessary to sift those out, determine what the real facts are, so to speak, and develop kind of an issues development, and then try to lay out the options and say, Governor, this is what you ought to do.
So that's what I'm doing.
Never is it called planning.
But that's what we're involved in.
What about state?
Does state planning have any appeal to you at all?
State level stuff?
None?
Not at all yet.
I think they're interested in private sector.
Well, we haven't known anybody to talk to us about state planning.
We don't know anything about state planning.
It's very seldom discussed in the department.
understanding regional planning is really not discussed anymore.
It's kind of funny that regional planning, again, I've worked with it off and on for my whole career.
Bye bye.
I'm sorry you're leaving.
Take care.
I'm really sold on regional planning.
And I guess I am because
I just know there's so many issues that can't be dealt with at the state level, so many issues that can't be dealt with the city level.
And our counties are just, you know, if you had counties like California, then you don't need regional planning, probably.
You have highly capable, strong planning and program staff within the county level.
And so, you know, the necessity for regional planning probably is maybe less.
I don't know.
But in Texas, we have nothing at the county level, fairly strong activities going on, particularly urban cities, big cities.
But in rural towns, no program staff.
And then the state level is really weak on planning and issue development.
So regional planning is a real good function to try to pull together city, county issues and be a link between the state of Texas.
Leon, what do you think the chances are of having a new state planning law written
or a state planning law written that would mandate certain actions by the state?
I think it's interesting.
Let me mention, I don't know how to tell you, but look at the second actual page on that task force.
The second page, if you look at the front of the document and just look at the actual
last LegalLink page.
The last one on that page is Special Committee on Organization of State Agencies.
Here.
Too bad they didn't number the pages.
Thank you.
Let me just bring this to your attention, because we're looking at how we could opt to restructure state government with this with this group.
My director is on this, this group and the governor appointed the chairman.
So we're gonna try to influence this this group, although their appointees from lieutenant governor and speaker on this whole issue of
how we reorganize.

We got into this whole discussion of super agencies, trying to instead of having 300 and some odd state agencies, try to have 18 super agencies with breakouts, maybe departments, maybe an environmental agency with air, water, whatnot under it, rather than having the independent little small agencies.
A number of people have testified that many states have gone away from the umbrella type agency because of numerous problems.
The umbrella agency concept was supposed to be big in the late 70s.
There are a number of states that did reorganization of state government and did the umbrella agency concept.
In fact, Jimmy Cotta
which was one of the earlier ones that reorganized Georgia and did that lumping of agencies.
But we've had a number of people testify that rather than that, we needed to really emphasize the governor forming these planning commissions of agency heads, which the governor can do now.
But, I mean, they're saying mandate it.
They're saying mandate reports at a certain time, mandate action, which is really the only way you'd probably appropriate dollars for it and so forth.
And what I'm saying is that would exactly be, I don't know that you'd call it a planning agency particularly, but it would be...
You know, time might be right for a piece of legislation that would require these kinds of planning functions.
Well, usually in an era of trouble, economic trouble, people are searching for answers of some type.
So what you could do is work with your students and come up with a strategy and
over there at the appropriate time.
Exactly.
Since they're all interested in city government, they don't care about mending state government?
Well, if we were, if Texas A&M were in Austin, I think that we'd have something of a different orientation towards state government in this department.
I don't think so.
We really don't get over there that often.
You see, the planning department in the University of Texas doesn't see any...
We don't see them.
That's them.
They're different.
They've always been different.
Yes, ma'am.
I think that the reason I'm not interested as much in it as a career, I'm interested in it as a career.
I want to work more with the teachers.
at the state level, because that means you don't feel like you're really working with people, you feel like you're working with a whole regional plan.
It's very necessary.
I just wonder if you don't think you're attacking that, but it's just, I want to work more with the grassroots and the people.
Where the action is.
Yeah, I want to see results, and I don't think that you will eventually, but I think it's slower moving at that level, because it hasn't been tested, and that's why we're in trouble.
Maintain good health so you live long enough to see the results of your work.
I'll try.
You can try.
With the size of your staff, what is the background of people coming in from public administration?
Or are they trained planners?
I was the first planner that had a degree in it, hired in the governor's office.
Ralph, you know, is an example.
I think it's a mixed bag now and now with budget planning being merged and heavy on the budget.
Most of their focus is like LBJ directors, the public administration.
You know, but I think state government in general, they're different planning shops there.
But I'm not trying to sell you.
I would say that any job that you have, you need to understand about the state level, how to deal with them, how to manipulate them or whatnot.
I would probably counter a little bit.
I think we probably see quite a few people, bodies in our office wanting issues to be dealt with similar to a city planning office.
I will say this.
Y'all may not see this a lot, but we have public broadcasting on our table, the network, and there's a lot of city stuff, you know, played late at night.
And particularly at the county level, every decision that's made is made open to the world.
Every decision that's made.
I saw the other night a consultant being selected, and the consultants were

drug out before the commission in the county commission and they testified before the commission and body of people in the background and everybody watching on TV and they were saying why why don't you think we all select you you know what's wrong with those guys next to you I mean it was a much more open process than state government
And I don't know, I guess it's better, but gee, that's something that's not done at that state level.

I mean, you would have consultants in independently to discuss their piece and then excuse them and get the next guy in, you know, that kind of thing, rather than having them right there before the world.
Leon, looking at this map of the Texas planning regions, which are distributed
The quality of performance by the various cogs in the state is very uneven.
We have one locally that 4 o'clock y'all have to be by.
I enjoyed coming.
And don't give up on the state, OK?
Yeah, see you.
If y'all need to run, don't feel compelled to stay.
It was good to be here with you.
Yes.
The quality of the work of the local COG is non-planning, shall we say.
What can be done about a job description in terms of sort of a possible mandating of certain levels of planning by the various COGs around the state?
Is there any hope for that sort of thing to happen that would give them a mission?
Well, it's real difficult to, even when we were funding them very extensively, it's difficult to mandate.
The whole philosophy of regional councils were that they were to provide local elected officials come together and form entities.
Obviously, there are certain things they have to do in order to get their federal and state funds.
But they are locally operated and owned, and there's always a point where the elected officials say, we ain't doing that.
And there's always that fine line.
I think the answer would be, yes, there ought to be more specific criteria given them.
The money is being cut back.
State level money is being cut back.
Now we're in a reduction mode rather than increasing mode, even with costs rising.
Our ability to really mandate those things might be limited by the fact that we just don't give them that much money.
But the unevenness all comes from the fact that the money, like the smaller cogs will get like $50,000 from the state.
And be a planning director and get $50,000 and say, you just go out and do all the planning you want to do for $50,000.
Of course, they job around and get their other federal and state dollars to try to keep the doors open.
But they don't have the discretionary money to do.
I mean, they've got to run the aging program, and they've got to run the job training program, and they've got to do the criminal justice stuff where they're distributing funds for crime fighting.
This is my complaint about them is that they're doing service-oriented programs.
They're not doing planning.
It's a service operation now.
That is where they've had to go.
The 701 HUD money was the glue money, as well as the state dollars.
And then there were several other generalist pots of money, and those are gone.
Another question I keep asking, why is it that Oregon, Florida, and California can get away with mandating planning, statewide planning,
when, for example, Oregon is hardly a wealthy state.
But they require it of every county and every city in the state.
And they've all done it.
I would probably say if you look at the revenue stream for those cities and counties, you will find that all those dollars come from the state.
Whereas our city and county governments operate off of...
ad valorem taxes.
So their money, I mean, they're allowed to do the ad valorem taxes by the state of Texas, but they don't have to ask for the money.
The money is theirs because they provide that taxation.
I don't know that that is totally the case, but I think that Oregonians, in this case, do try to exercise a great deal of equity.
so that if state government does mandate something, I think that state government feels a responsibility for funding the opportunity to fulfill the mandate.
Yeah, that's probably true.
I think, I was just thinking about New Mexico.
All the revenue is brought up to the state level, and then they spew it back to the cities and counties based on, you know, a funding, you know, deal.
And they, you know, I don't know exactly how they distribute it, but that, you know, it makes a lot of difference.
They will give you
these tax dollars if you will do these things.

And I guess, for the record or anybody else, city and county government associations, that's a major complaint with them, that state government tends to lay mandates on city and county and other entities without the appropriate resources to get it done.
And to some extent, that's true in state government.
Of course, the feds have done that, too.
Oh, sure.
It trickles down through the beds.
I had a quick question for you, and I guess a statement coming back to one of your questions and the interest of why people aren't interested in estate planning.
In my situation, I'm interested in urban design, and does the state at any level offer that?
to a planter coming out of school, urban design.
What do you mean by that?
Well, do they use...
I mean, what...
I know the city uses, like, an urban designer, but...
When you say urban design, what do you mean?
What kind of thing would you envision designing?
More or less like a dart and so on, train stations, cityscape and so on.
Well, that's obviously going to have to be a city.
Yeah, that's obviously going to have to be a city.

But when you said urban design, the transportation planning function within the highway department, for example, has a heck of a lot to do with what goes on within a city, a city of Houston or Dallas or whatever else, although a lot of that's done locally.
But the freeway systems and all that kind of stuff has a lot to do with that.
But I think, yeah, I think your urban design is primarily done by the urban areas, urban cities.
And in my case, I didn't think the state would have that.
No, I think your interest, you'd be better served in the larger urban areas.
It's kind of interesting because I'm, you know, quite frankly, I'm not sure just how much...
urban design is done within Dallas and Houston and San Antonio.
Well, I'm not either.
I was going to mention that during the break between semesters I spent in Switzerland.
And there you have a country that just reeks of urban design.
And it's all consistent within the entire country.
The bridges are all, they're just pure works of art.
And they use minimal materials.
and a maximum of thoughtful engineering design, rather than the reverse that we do in this country.
And all the signing and so forth is very carefully studied.
And the placement of outdoor advertising, they have a lot of it.
But it's done in a way that it's not visually disruptive.
And it can be done.
I don't think that simply because it's a state that it
is impossible, even a large state like Texas, because there we're dealing with a whole country composed of, in their case, cantons.
They have a central planning agency for the federal government.
They do, out of Barron.
And all things are planned out of that office?
And they have a national plan.
They put all of their resources in those kinds of things rather than military spending?
They put a lot of money into military spending.
That's the reason that they stayed neutral during the Second World War.
Every...
They don't spend that many dollars in their... Percentage-wise, it's very high.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
In all of those mountains, you have artillery, and they're pointed in all sorts of directions, namely in Germany.
Oh.
Yeah.
And they come up hydraulically out of the ground.
They look like farmers...
hay, drying, pots, and so forth.
But it's all camouflage.
In the Department of Commerce packet, it talks about how the commission should look at, or how they should look at other states' plans.
Is that something that is done a lot?
Is it keeping up with what other states are up to?
It's kind of interesting.
On this consolidation task force,
Yes, the Consolidation Task Force.
Every agency, they call the agencies in.
Every agency is telling them what they do and so forth.
It seemed like the question always got around, well, how do other states do what you bid?
And it's kind of funny that it's gotten where now.
That's the first question asked.
How do you compare?
How do we rank with other states?
How do we, you know...
And we always rank low in terms of state spending per capita or whatnot.
That's a fairly new attitude in state government.
Oh, it is.
Most of the time, we were proud of underspending.
And still, I'm not sure we're away from that.
Well, the point I'm making, too, is that it was almost forbidden to mention

experience gained from other states texas had its own way of doing things and you could not compare with other states because they all did it wrong well they all did it wrong for texas i'm sorry yes yeah well you met uh in the strategic economic policy commission the mission one of the mission is to lead the development of a comprehensive plan for the state which will provide both long-term direction
and placing priority on other short-term actions to improve the state's economy.
Considering the, what, because this was established in 19, I don't know when it was.
Well, the regions were actually delineated in 68, the study was done, yeah.
But considering the 1968 delineation, we have about 24 regions.
How do you reconcile the objectives or goals of these 24 different
counties into one state objective?
Well, I'm not sure what the strategy is going to be of the commission.
I know the COGS, the regional councils, we call them COGS sometimes, regional councils are offering to feed in to this commission.
They've already met a couple of times, and they're offering to provide forums at the 24 regional levels.

provide free space and all this kind of stuff to to help you know with this input into the to the plan I'm sure they'll probably play a role I'm not sure how much quite frankly Commerce if it has a weakness right now is recording it has a weakness right now it's heavily weighted toward businessmen and
it doesn't really have much of a governmental slant.
So I'm not sure how that will all play out.
But all the government appointees are businessmen-oriented, focused.
So I'm not real sure how comfortable the department's going to be working with regional entities.
But I think you make a good point.
I think the reasons certainly would be, even though, as Bob says, they're probably not
particularly good are doing much planning now.
They're probably as good as most folks out there that are doing planning.
You start looking at other governmental entities.
I could be proven wrong within some of the major urban areas, but you go to Podunk, a little town, and they're zoning.
They throw in zoning ordinances and stuff, but there's really not much planning involved.
But I appreciate your comment or your question.
We're going to be encouraging that from our office.
We're going to be encouraging the use of regional council in that process.
I would certainly like to see a job description at least suggested by state government for COGS in terms of
what would be nice to see them do in terms of planning?
It could start out being suggested.
You don't see their law.
You see their law lately?
The law has some pretty heavy statements about what they should do.
If you'll get the last directory, look at the back at the Article 1011M, I would be surprised if you wouldn't think that sounds pretty, pretty good.
But someone's going to have to say, you see the law?
Do it.
and here's some money that you can get it done with.
It sounds pretty comprehensive planning-oriented, involving all the functional planning components and so forth.
I'll have to take a look.
You might look at it.
Thank you all.
Appreciate it.
Thank you very much, Leon.
Yes.
Thank you.
